it was a Mr. Gilchrist. I think he was the one that 
actually hired me. He was the one that actually

28:08.510 --> 28:10.272
hired me. Now, it was a cockeyed operational 
because he hired me, but I was in the School of Arts

28:11.773 --> 28:20.562
and Science in the literary school. And did you 
decide to come to A&M? Did they offer you a more

28:24.189 --> 28:26.291
attractive position? All of it was a boost in rank 
and a boost in pay.

28:32.959 --> 28:34.601
And this was toward the end of the Depression now. 
This is 37? 38. 38. This is

28:36.903 --> 28:42.650
right at the tail end of the Depression. Yeah, I 
think so. And traditionally, this is the way

28:45.253 --> 28:49.958
chemical engineering Originally, to go into the 
history of this stuff, originally

28:51.693 --> 29:06.448
they used to teach industrial chemistry in the 
School of Arts and Science. How you made sulfuric

29:06.468 --> 29:16.038
acid and just a descriptive discussion of how you 
made various materials. And then The MIT people

29:19.553 --> 29:33.851
came out with a new idea, which

29:19.553 --> 29:33.851
they wrote a book called Unit Operations.

29:34.772 --> 29:41.261
And here it studied different kinds of heat 
transfer. Well, the first one is fluid flow.

29:44.244 --> 29:48.750
Pressure drops through a pipe, whether you're 
pumping oil or whether you're pumping water or

29:49.102 --> 29:52.045
whatever. The same fundamentals will apply 
regardless of what you're pumping. The same thing

29:57.390 --> 30:00.073
is true in heat transfer. If you're heating 
something up, the same fundamentals would apply

30:00.133 --> 30:08.861
whether you're heating oil or whether you're 
heating water. And that same idea was taken into

30:10.403 --> 30:18.130
all kinds of so-called unit operations, fluid 
flow, heat transfer, distillation, the

30:18.886 --> 30:28.895
fundamentals of what you are doing, rather than 
the descriptive of how to make sulfuric acid. And

30:28.915 --> 30:34.961
that idea was brand new in chemical engineering, 
in teaching. Instead of a descriptive course, it

30:35.161 --> 30:38.985
was a how to do it course. And that started MIT and, 
of course, the northern schools, Wisconsin.

30:48.383 --> 30:53.909
Those schools picked it up and put it in, in 
chemical engineering. But it took quite a while

30:53.929 --> 31:00.436
for the country boy schools, and I don't mean that 
he... No. It took quite a while for that idea to get

31:00.556 --> 31:05.862
out to the smaller schools. It's really kind of 
unusual, because here you had a school that was

31:06.002 --> 31:12.909
supposedly teaching the how-to-do of various 
things. It was originally planned. had

31:15.316 --> 31:18.480
agriculture teaching people how to do it. It's 
unusual. Well, there wasn't anybody had written a

31:20.804 --> 31:29.015
book on this so-called unit operations book put 
out by the MIT people. It was brand new. About 1920,

31:33.401 --> 31:38.709
that book came out. Then you came here now in the 
fall of 38. Fall of 38, as a full professor. Right.

31:45.923 --> 31:48.848
With full teaching load? Yeah, I think so. Well, a 
little bit of time supposed to be for research, but

31:50.110 --> 31:55.178
not very much in those days. And at that time, I 
believe, T.O. Walton was president. Right.

32:00.707 --> 32:01.268
That's right. C.C. Hedges was head of the 
chemistry department. C.C. Hedges. Cut the

32:14.345 --> 32:39.357
Well, Mr.

32:14.345 --> 32:39.357
Gilchrist, who was Dean of Engineering, wanted to 
get the chemical engineering taught in the School

32:14.345 --> 32:39.357
of Engineering under him, rather than in the 
School of Arts and Science.

32:41.395 --> 32:43.757
So he approached me, would I be willing? And once I 
told him I'd be willing, but I couldn't take any

32:43.898 --> 32:50.224
sides in the matter. And he understood that. And so 
they used to have a board of directors meeting to

32:54.108 --> 33:03.037
graduate, legally graduate the students. And 
then they'd have a reception for the parents after

33:05.439 --> 33:11.065
the graduation. And all the staff used to go to that 
reception to meet the parents of the students. So

33:19.063 --> 33:22.151
Mr. Gilchrist beckoned me over. You're going to be 
working for me this summer. So the same board of

33:25.419 --> 33:30.792
directors that had graduated the students, they 
had decided to separate the department. So he sort

33:32.298 --> 33:34.422
of rammed it through the board of directors. Oh 
yes, he was for that all the time. Do you think he had

33:36.746 --> 33:40.914
any opposition to forming a chemical engineering 
department? Oh yes, the old boy Hedges, Professor

33:41.154 --> 33:44.942
C.C. Hedges, didn't want to let it go. He didn't 
want to lose his chemical engineering section.

33:48.989 --> 33:49.630
That's right. It's only normal, I suppose. And 
then this was what, 39 and 40? No, about 41, I think.

33:57.327 --> 33:57.587
41. I think it was about 41. And Mr.

33:59.871 --> 34:13.515
Gilchrist, the old,

33:59.871 --> 34:13.515
had the old geology building. I don't know whether 
it's... They taught petroleum in it for a long

34:16.739 --> 34:20.002
time. That one used to have a tower on it. Used to 
have a water tank in it. Right, right, a water tank

34:23.165 --> 34:25.948
inside of that tower, right. And so he said, we'll 
put you over there this summer, but it won't be long

34:27.530 --> 34:39.942
before we have a regular chemical engineering 
building for you. About two or three years it'll

34:40.883 --> 34:43.506
take to get us separated. And that was from about 41 
to about three or four years ago when they built

34:44.212 --> 34:57.018
this new engineering building up on the corner, 
maybe five years ago. So we were in that old geology

34:57.038 --> 35:02.288
building for many years. And then they built a... 
Every time somebody moved out, I'd get my foot in

35:03.736 --> 35:09.843
the door to get a few extra rooms. They built a very 
nice... It used to be petroleum, too, in there.

35:16.230 --> 35:19.073
Chemical engineering has to do with the 
distilling of the oil. The petroleum engineering

35:21.395 --> 35:29.424
has to do hunting the oil, finding the oil, and 
getting it up out of the ground and transporting it

35:21.395 --> 35:29.424
through their pipelines. And then chemical 
engineers take over at a refinery and have to do

35:33.149 --> 35:36.233
with the separation of the products. When was the 
department accredited? Do you remember? Say, no,

35:41.341 --> 35:42.342
I don't. I'd have to, it was, we went through a long, 
hard series of troubles in getting us accredited.

35:51.936 --> 36:01.890
First was, there's a lot of things, getting the 
equipment and getting enough staff and I don't

35:51.936 --> 36:01.890
recall. I'd have to look it up. Let's drop back a 
minute now. We've got up into the 40s. When you

36:07.646 --> 36:12.230
first came here, do you have any impressions of, 
say, President Walton? He was here until 1943.

36:13.871 --> 36:18.135
Well, I thought he was a very good president. Did 
you have any personal relationship with him at

36:18.155 --> 36:20.878
all? Oh. Did you ever get called into his office to 
talk to him?

36:32.279 --> 36:33.060
I sure did. Harrington, too.

36:43.593 --> 36:50.301
One of the things that I inherited was cotton seed. 
They do a lot of cotton seed, growing cotton here

36:50.321 --> 37:01.054
and making cotton seed oil and chicken feed out of 
what's left after you squeeze So that was going on

37:01.658 --> 37:10.148
when I came, but I inherited a lot of that. And so we 
had this short course in cottonseed oil. And it

37:19.759 --> 37:21.201
wasn't too large. About 80 and 90 people would come 
to it. Is it in the summertime? Usually, yes. And

37:29.831 --> 37:31.193
then...

37:33.502 --> 37:39.429
So

37:33.502 --> 37:39.429
we'd had that. I'd had that experience with that 
cottonseed short course. Then I started a, well,

37:42.993 --> 37:54.385
I'd take our students out on inspection trips. And 
things had changed so much since I was a boy in a

37:54.405 --> 38:03.255
refinery, why they had automatic recording 
instruments and control instruments. If you

38:08.494 --> 38:17.207
wanted to change a valve or read a gauge, you'd have 
to climb a steel ladder to read it and twist the

38:08.494 --> 38:17.207
valve yourself. Whereas I'd come down here quite a 
few years later, and they had recording

38:18.809 --> 38:27.042
instruments and control. You didn't have to do all 
of that. You had a little house, a regular house,

38:28.924 --> 38:32.770
where they had these recording instruments in. 
And so I thought we should teach some of that. And I

38:39.202 --> 38:43.090
didn't know anything about automatic control or 
the like. And I wrote to a bunch of companies that

38:44.031 --> 38:50.483
made these instruments, asking for their 
catalogs and information. And one afternoon, a

38:51.966 --> 38:56.715
chap showed up in my office. from one of these big 
companies and said, we've had requests for

38:56.932 --> 39:04.980
information from all kinds of people, but we never 
had a request from a college professor. What did

39:05.080 --> 39:06.481
you want to know for? So I told him what I had in mind 
of teaching that stuff in our classes, and he

39:08.122 --> 39:21.435
thought that was a very fine idea and agreed to work 
with me. And then he said, well, it sure would be

39:21.495 --> 39:26.820
good if we could get some of these older people 
acquainted with the operations of these

39:27.222 --> 39:33.632
instruments, as well as your new students just 
coming through. So having been associated with

39:34.574 --> 39:40.343
this oilseed course, I said, well, maybe we can do 
that, too. And so we started an instrumentation

39:41.986 --> 39:46.673
short course. And it was very, very elementary at 
the start. We'd meet in the classrooms. have the

39:52.450 --> 39:58.660
exhibits in the halls of the building, and it has 
developed very, very fine. That's still going on?

39:59.782 --> 40:00.924
It's still going on. And the new student center in 
1950, when we had the student center built, why,

40:01.926 --> 40:10.641
that was a big help. And we get about 600, 700 people 
attend it now, and they come from all over the

40:11.542 --> 40:17.412
country. It was the first one that got started, 
even before there's an Instruments Society of

40:17.982 --> 40:25.971
America that got started now. Do you remember the 
year you held your first meeting? Oh, I think I'd

40:30.015 --> 40:34.920
have to look this up, too, about 41, 42. I

40:35.141 --> 40:43.950
can get all of this factual material. And...

40:49.420 --> 40:51.442
So it's mighty fine. I've made mighty fine friends 
in that organization. Well, where I got to know

40:55.786 --> 41:07.717
these presidents a little bit more,

40:55.786 --> 41:07.717
as you know, a lot of these guys from industry like 
to have a drink. And there's a lot of salesmen

41:08.117 --> 41:10.139
around. And they're selling the instruments. And 
the people from the big companies will be using the

41:12.501 --> 41:17.706
instruments.

41:19.441 --> 41:28.333
And so I got called down to the president's

41:19.441 --> 41:28.333
office. They found five bottles, whiskey 
bottles, in

41:29.294 --> 41:41.189
your

41:29.294 --> 41:41.189
wastebaskets in the room. What room is this? In the 
student center here on the campus. And there's not

41:48.432 --> 41:52.938
supposed to be any... What president was this in 
the country? Well, I think it was Walton was the

41:53.018 --> 42:01.309
first one, and it was just when Harrington was 
taken over. And Harrington was a teacher in the

42:01.790 --> 42:05.895
chemistry department. Well, let's see. Walton 
was here until 1943, and then Bolton until 1944,

42:07.177 --> 42:16.409
and then Gib Gilchrist until 1948, and Bolton 
again, and then Harrington the first time in 1950.

42:16.690 --> 42:16.870
Yeah. Well, anyway, every little while this thing 
would happen.

42:24.586 --> 42:26.868
So I had gotten called down there. I know 
Harrington, he sure didn't want to do it because he

42:26.888 --> 42:35.676
lived down the street from me before he got to be 
president. But he had to do it. And when I got told

42:38.878 --> 42:46.165
that they found him in the wastebaskets of the 
room, I put out the word. If any time you guys empty a

42:46.786 --> 42:53.976
bottle here on the campus, why, put it in your 
suitcase and take it home with you. And I never had

42:53.996 --> 42:58.983
any trouble from then on.

43:00.585 --> 43:04.751
So that's how I originally got to... I mean, I got 
called down to the president's office a couple of

43:05.532 --> 43:09.398
times. One was real bad.

43:14.905 --> 43:16.708
There was one... over in the board of directors 
house. And one of the guys really got intoxicated

43:22.230 --> 43:27.098
over in the board. You don't remember our old 
student center across the street from the,

43:28.299 --> 43:40.738
remember when they crossed the street from the 
mess hall? right next to the old president's

43:41.107 --> 43:43.190
house. This used to be the Aggieland Inn? 
Aggieland Inn, yeah. I've seen pictures. It was

43:45.954 --> 43:47.736
torn down right as I— Yeah. Well, anyway, several 
years ago. Well,

43:50.400 --> 44:00.914
they used to have displays in there. It was quite 
elementary. But it's—we've changed things up and

44:03.617 --> 44:10.827
hold them now at the end of the semester. Well,

44:11.060 --> 44:20.051
digress a little bit here.

44:24.276 --> 44:27.960
What do you remember of the end of the Depression 
here on the campus? Was there many hardships from

44:28.100 --> 44:31.264
the teaching faculty? Did

44:31.905 --> 44:37.692
anybody know there was a Depression going on here? 
I don't remember too much about that. Was it an

44:42.169 --> 44:48.460
island of relative prosperity in a country that 
was having hard times? We had a harder time to get

44:49.763 --> 44:53.610
jobs for the students. I worked very closely with 
the students in getting jobs. That was something

44:58.278 --> 45:02.245
that I was always... good relations with the 
students. In fact, the matter is, they gave me an

45:05.584 --> 45:08.407
automobile when I retired. Yes, I know.

45:12.471 --> 45:28.406
Well, anyway,

45:12.471 --> 45:28.406
working hard, that was the hardest thing, is 
getting jobs for the students.

45:28.426 --> 45:30.308
But I don't recall that we had

45:34.186 --> 45:35.131
trouble. See, I was here and our staff was pretty 
well fixed.

